tunities and challenges in this growing field. In addition to describing actual designs and measures, the chapters includes suggestions for addressing the specific challenges of working in a policy setting, such as a long time horizon for achieving meaningful change. To illuminate and advance this area of evaluation practice, the authors draw on over 30 years of evaluation experience; collective wisdom based on a new, large-scale survey of evaluators in the field; and in-depth case studies on diverse issues-from the environment, to public health, to human rights. Ideal for evaluators, change makers, and funders, this book is the definitive guide to advocacy and policy change evaluation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPolicy sciencesxEvaluation. 0aPolitical planningxEvaluation. 0aSocial advocacyxEvaluation. 4aAdvocacy and policy change evaluation. 4aAdvocacy. 4aEvaluation design. 4aMethods. 4aNonprofits. 4aPolicy change. 4aPolicymaking. 4aPublic policy. 4aStrategic learning. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Advocacy.2bisacsh1 aBrindis, Claire, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360233540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602335.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles